<tt>Tue Oct  7 18:30:05 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ok. I opened this thread this morning so that a nice lady could post some stuff about building watchfires. She said that she wasn't able to access this website, and told me to go ahead and kick things off. <br><br>
I received, on my newsreader, the following post from the Usenet Newsgroup - alt.war.vietnam - last year, about Nov 1. The lady who posted this message makes mention of her email address, but I hesitate to post it here. <br><br>
So here is her posting, followed by my response from about a year ago.<br><br>
***********************************************************<br>
A couple of years ago someone posted an article about the Watchfires group...once a year they light watchfires to guide wandering warriors home..at least that's what I gathered from it.  I am not associated with<br>
the group, and I don't know how to get in touch with them.  But each year since we have lit watchfires around the country this time of year. Without an official date, I chose Nov 1-2 --really Nov. 1 but I didn't get this out in time and it's not too late.<br><br>
Anyway, this is a very holy day of the year in many cultures...Irish, Mexican, all Catholic and perhaps other Christian.  Also there are<br>
pre-christian traditions involved, and I think the original watchfire tradition is from the Mohawk Indians -- I don't know about other cultures I am ommitting...<br><br>
So, if you would like to light a fire tonight, or today, no matter how small or large, please do...Next year we'll try to be more organized.  A friend has written a beautiful poem about it.  I can't post without permission but if you email me I'll see if I can mail you the poem.<br><br>
And let me know if you decide to do this, or if you know anything official about the Watchfire Association.<br><br>
It just strikes me as so applicable to the Vietnam situation -- so many homeless people who could participate..so many people who can't afford to go to the wall or can't bring themselves too, so many families that don't understand....and think what a fire would have meant some cold monsoon night..<br><br>
 M. Garvey<br><br>
***********************************************************<br><br>
My response:<br><br>
Your message struck a familiar chord. Thomas Hardy , in *The Return of The  Native*, mentions these fires as being  &quot;the lineal descendents from jumbled Druidical rites and Saxon ceremonies&quot;.<br><br>
Also, in the 3rd Chapter he states, &quot;Moreover to light a fire is the instinctive and resistant act of man when, at the winter ingress, the curfew is sounded throughout nature. It indicates a spontaneous, Prometean rebelliousness against the fiat that this recurrent season shall bring foul times, cold darkness, misery and death.&quot;<br><br>
Gives me the chills, just thinking about it. Thanks for the note about Vietnam. I hope readers excuse my off topic response. Yes...I will light a fire tonight.<br><br>
Tom Dier
